\fs32 \cf2 Hi Oliver. \'a0This is fun. \'a0I took a look at the Pettigrew paper (and also sent him a copy of mine, mentioning your referral). \'a0He does have a similar state structure, and similar data -- empirical win probabilities given goal and manpower differential. \'a0But his model for win probabilities is not derived from the Markov state-transition equations (Chapman-Kolmogorov) -- rather, he fits polynomial functions to the observed win probabilities to obtain smooth curves, and then uses those as the basis for computing WPA. \'a0While numerically the results are probably close to what we have (assuming the curves are well-fit, which they appear to be), the nice thing about the direct Markov approach is that the observed win probabilities are not used anywhere to calibrate the model -- only the observed state transition rates are used to deduce the win probabilities. \'a0In this way, I would argue that we have a better test of the Markov assumptions (as covered in the appendix to our paper). \'a0Also, not clear how curve fitting would handle overtime properly without putting in explicit conditions that tie games at the end of overtime must yield a 50% win probability (or empirical equivalent if not exactly 50%).\
\
As for Hamilton- Jacobi, yes, I know about these sorts of models in other contexts -- a recent paper on optimal control and terrorism is attached. \'a0The only application in hockey I know of is the optimal time to pull the goalie papers -- the paper by Al Washburn at the Naval Postgraduate School from several years ago is a very nice example. \'a0I will go back to your paper to see just how you are using this. \'a0I confess complete ignorance of machine learning, which might be a good reason to collaborate as I could learn from you!\
\
Hope you are enjoying yourself! \'a0Best, Ed K.\
