Pettigrew also presents a continuous Poission model and uses second-by-second discretization. In Markov game theory the basic approach is to solve the differential equation (the Hamilton-Jacobi equation https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamilton%E2%80%93Jacobi%E2%80%93Bellman_equation). I think I saw a solution given for the special case of Poisson transitions models somewhere. Solving for optimal actions isn\'92t the same thing as solving for w(x,y,t), but the existing mathematics could be a starting point. If you are interested in discussing or even collaborating on this, we could use the help :-) But I understand that you are busy.\
\
Great idea about comparing win probability added with independent quality measures. We\'92ve looked at salary so far. The UAI reviewers also suggested using WPA to make predictions, perhaps about which players will score points next season, or about which teams will win. Pettigrew emphasizes consistency of win probability added across seasons as an important desideratum. \
\
Thank you for the insightful comments, and taking the time to write them down, it\'92s very helpful!\
