RE: home ice advantage, I don\'92t really have an explanation for why the goal scoring rates are higher for the home team after adjusting for penalties. \'a0However, Toby Moskowitz, an economist and co-author of Scorecasting where the referee-bias argument is explained in some detail, is visiting Yale, and I asked him about this. \'a0He suggested that in addition to penalties, referees could exercise home ice bias by calling faceoffs in more advantageous ways (e.g. whether to stop play at all, or whether a faceoff is inside or outside the blue line, etc.). \'a0That seems to be something that you could check with your richer event data. \'a0Another economist here had a more game theoretic explanation that I find bizarre but apparently many of the economists find plausible, and that is that the visiting team players are cognizant of the *threat* of penalties being called more liberally against them as compared to the home team, and this causes them to play more cautiously, which in turn leads to lower goal scoring rates. \'a0Now, having grown up with hockey (I grew up in Saskatoon, Saskatchewan), I just have a hard time thinking that in the heat of a game, players could be occupied with such second order thinking. \'a0But, if you have a way of judging shot quality, then perhaps you can show that after adjusting for manpower differential, the home team has higher shot quality (either per shot, or perhaps at a higher rate; both presumably would lead to higher goal scoring rates).\
\
Finally, while I appreciate your excitement for the continuous model, I have to confess that the numerical solution resorts to discretization at a second-by-second level, but it just seemed much more natural to me to formulate the problem as a continuous process. \'a0This is also stated in the paper. \'a0Nonetheless I am also excited by the actual graph of w(x,y,t), especially when x=0 and t puts you in overtime \'96 that gives the comet-looking \'93swoosh\'94 at the end of the graph, and I love how everything converges back to \'bd if the game remains tied at the end of overtime regardless of manpower difference (due of course to the ensuing shootout).\
\
Anyway, thanks again for your note. \'a0We are hoping to get out a second paper that focuses on evaluating the win probability added for NHL players over four years, and comparing these results to other quality measures \'96 e.g. to the \'93three stars\'94 selected each game collectively have a distribution of win probability added that dominates the non-stars, does WPA match well with All Star or MVP selections, etc. \'a0But all that remains work in progress.\
\
